<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18460202-662">
               <interp inst="t18460202-662" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18460202"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18460202-662" type="date" value="18460202"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18460202-662-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-662-18460202 t18460202-662-offence-1 t18460202-662-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>662. <persName id="def1-662-18460202" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-662-18460202" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-662-18460202" type="surname" value="YOUNG"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-662-18460202" type="given" value="ALBORN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">ALBORN YOUNG</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18460202-662-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18460202-662-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18460202-662-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp> for stealing, on the <rs id="t18460202-cd-31" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18460202-662-offence-1 t18460202-cd-31"></join>22nd of Jan</rs>., 13 dwts. 7 grains of gold, value 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18460202-name-1118" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1118" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1118" type="surname" value="SEYMOUR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1118" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18460202-662-offence-1 t18460202-name-1118"></join>William Seymour</persName> and another, his masters.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-1119" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1119" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1119" type="surname" value="SEYMOUR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1119" type="given" value="WM"></interp>WM. SEYMOUR</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in partnership with my son James Edward Seymour, as gold-beaters, at Long-acre—we have also an establishment at Peckham, where we employ apprentices—the prisoner was employed there as foreman—the witness Isaacs is an apprentice of ours—we supply the prisoner with the necessary tools and gold to work, five beatings at a time, 2oz. 7dwts. in the beating—it is first beaten out, and then made into leaf—a certain quan<lb></lb>tity of what is called <hi rend="italic">shurf</hi> comes off—that is preserved and delivered to me as well as the leaves, and is melted—in Nov. last I delivered the prisoner, five of these rolls—I did not receive any of it back—I applied to him for it, and on the 21st of Jan. I ordered him to get his work up and give it me—I went on the following Monday to Peckham, and asked if his work was up—he said, "not quite, I shall not long about it"—(he had asked me on the previous Wednesday to lend him money, which I had declined)—he then said, "I am a beating and a half deficient, I have done wrong, look over it, and I will work it out"—I said no—I examined the work, and discovered a deficiency of 3 dwts. more than a beating and a half—I sent for a constable and gave him in charge.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had he a child lying dead at that time? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He had, and he has one child besides—there is what its called stone dirt, part of which is a perquisite of the workman—it is the sweepings out of</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184602020195"></xptr>
               <p>the stove—the prisoner had seven or eight persons employed under him, some are girls and women—about five persons would be employed under him to do these five beatings—he might have eight or nine—Isaacs has been in our employment about two months—he had worked for us before, in Long<lb></lb>acre, about two years back—I do not know what he was doing in the mean<lb></lb>time—he came down and asked for work, and we employed him—he made no communication to me till the day he was about to be sworn.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did Isaacs behave honestly and respectably when with you before? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I believe there was some little <hi rend="italic">thingamy</hi> or fall out between him and my son—the prisoner did not attribute his deficiency to Isaacs or anybody.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-1120" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1120" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1120" type="surname" value="ISAACS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1120" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE ISAACS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a journeyman gold-beater, and work for Mr. Seymour, at Peckham—on the 21st of Jan. I went with the prisoner to several public-houses, and afterwards went home with him to the factory, about half-past twelve—he said to me, "Will you work all night? I am going to work"—I said I would—we went into the shop, and he said, "I shall melt my stone-dirt"—he melted it, and there was 3dwts. 6 grains—he said, "That won't do, I must have more"—he then went to his box in which his <hi rend="italic">shruf</hi> was kept, took some gold out, weighed it, put it in, and melted it—there was 13 dwts. 7 grains, to the best of my recollection—he said that would do to pay for the funeral of his child, and get his wife a black gown—he told me on the Wednesday that he had asked Mr. Seymour to lend him 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., and he had refused, and he then remarked, "Well, he has refused to lend me the 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., I will have 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. worth out of the old b—"—he went to town at four o'clock next day with his wife, and said he was going to sell the gold—I saw him again on Friday morning, and he asked me to go to Nunhead<lb></lb>cemetery with him about a piece of ground—at we were coming back he told me he had sold the gold, he had taken it to Mr. Groser first, and he refused to buy it, as it was between the lights, and he said, to the best of my recollec<lb></lb>tion, that he had sold it to Mr. Collingridge—I could not swear to the name, but it ended with a <hi rend="italic">ridge</hi>, and was in Wilderness-row—he said he got 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. for it—he said to me, "I hope you will keep it <hi rend="italic">dark</hi>, for if you <hi rend="italic">come it</hi> I shall get <hi rend="italic">lagged</hi>, and I should look pretty in chains"—I did not say anything about it on that account till I was on my oath before the Magistrate.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Have you worked for a Mr. Laws? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I cannot tell why I left him, it is so long ago—I belive something was said about some silver concealed behind the weights—I was discharged on suspicion of that—I was discharged by Mr. Seymour's son on account of the work not turning out well—I did not take advantage of the prisoner being partially intoxi<lb></lb>cated, and melt this gold myself—I swear that—I sat down and smoked my pipe for about an hour, and had some coffee, and then went to bed—the dead child was in the next room—I was not astonished to hear such language as keeping it <hi rend="italic">dark</hi>, and bring <hi rend="italic">lagged</hi>, because I have heard it often before among gold-beaters—Mr. Seymour took me before the Magistrate—he said, "I want you to speak the truth, and nothing but the truth, and I hope you will answer"—I did not go till I was compelled.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-1121" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1121" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1121" type="surname" value="GROSER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1121" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM GROSER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a gold refiner, and live in Red Lion-street, clerkenwell—on the 21st or 22nd of Jan. I remember a short man cominginto my shop, about five o'clock, between the lights—he was about the heightof the prisoner, and his general appearance—I could not see his face distinctly—I was very busy at the other end of the premises, and finding he was a cus<lb></lb>tomer I did not like I got rid of him immediately—he put down a grain of gold—pushed it from me saying, "This will not suit me, neither the time of night nor the article"—he said something about lighting up—I said, "You</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184602020196"></xptr>
               <p>may bring it in the morning, if you want me to purchase it," and I retired and left him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> You cannot say whether it was the prisoner or not? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I cannot.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-1122" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1122" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1122" type="surname" value="DUNNELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1122" type="given" value="THOMAS JENKINS"></interp>THOMAS JENKINS DUNNELL</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the prosecutor's son-in-law, and occa<lb></lb>sionally look after his business at Peckham—the prisoner has the sole charge of the gold delivered at that workshop—in Jan. I examined the gold deli<lb></lb>vered there, and found a deficiency of 3oz. 13dwts., which is worth about 15<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I heard Mr. Seymour ask him if his work was up—he said, "No, not quite—I am a beating and a half deficient—I have done wrong—if you will look over it, I will work it out"—I went and fetched a policeman.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> I believe Mr. Seymour said, "He means he will work it further into me?" <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—at that time we had not ascertained any deficiency, only what he stated himself—the work was given to other parties to finish.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-1123" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1123" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1123" type="surname" value="TAPLIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1123" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN TAPLIN</persName>
                  </hi>. I finished this work—it weighed loz. only—it ought to have weighed 4oz. 14dwts.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-1124" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1124" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1124" type="surname" value="WRIGHT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1124" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>SAMUEL WRIGHT</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman.</hi>) I took the prisoner into custody.</p>
               <p>
